WEBVTT

00:02.169 --> 00:03.794
<i> - Dozens of the best</i>
<i> bladesmiths in America</i>

00:03.838 --> 00:05.504
<i> have gone head-to-head</i>
<i> for the chance to win</i>

00:05.548 --> 00:06.547
<i> "Forged in Fire."</i>

00:06.590 --> 00:08.674
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:08.718 --> 00:10.926
<i> While some of these elite</i>
<i> craftsmen have succeeded...</i>

00:10.970 --> 00:13.345
- Thank you.
<i> - Many more have fallen short.</i>

00:13.389 --> 00:15.723
<i> Clarence, Brandon,</i>
<i> JD, Gabriel,</i>

00:15.766 --> 00:17.891
your blade did not make the cut.

00:17.935 --> 00:19.768
<i> - Tonight, for the first time,</i>

00:19.812 --> 00:21.562
<i> four eliminated competitors</i>
<i> return</i>

00:21.605 --> 00:24.064
<i> for a shot at redemption.</i>

00:24.108 --> 00:26.525
- My biggest concern
right now is not finishing.

00:26.569 --> 00:29.236
<i> - Only one will take home</i>
<i> $10,000</i>

00:29.280 --> 00:31.405
<i> and finally earn the title</i>

00:31.449 --> 00:33.490
<i> "Forged in Fire" champion.</i>

00:33.534 --> 00:39.455
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

00:41.459 --> 00:42.958
<i> - My name is Gabriel Bell,</i>

00:43.002 --> 00:45.127
and I've been bladesmithing
my entire life.

00:45.171 --> 00:47.755
<i> Competing the first time,</i>
<i> it was a real big shock</i>

00:47.798 --> 00:50.174
<i> to have three hours</i>
<i> to forge a blade.</i>

00:50.217 --> 00:51.967
<i> I'll usually spend</i>
<i> more than three hours</i>

00:52.011 --> 00:54.178
<i> just forging a blade</i>
<i> before heat-treating.</i>

00:54.221 --> 00:56.346
<i> So it's an incredible</i>
<i> time crunch.</i>

00:56.390 --> 00:57.556
I'm hoping
that this time around,

00:57.600 --> 00:59.433
<i>I won't make any silly mistakes</i>

00:59.477 --> 01:01.643
<i> that cost me time</i>
<i> and send me home.</i>

01:01.687 --> 01:03.145
<i> - My name is Clarence Jackson,</i>

01:03.189 --> 01:05.564
and I've been making blades
for nine years.

01:05.608 --> 01:08.650
<i> I went home the first time</i>
<i> because I cracked my blade.</i>

01:08.694 --> 01:10.736
- Did Clarence just put
his blade in the water?

01:10.780 --> 01:12.613
<i> - That's not happening</i>
<i> this time.</i>

01:12.656 --> 01:14.198
I'm here to win the 10,000,

01:14.241 --> 01:17.034
<i> because I have a new baby</i>
<i> on the way.</i>

01:17.078 --> 01:18.827
<i> - My name is Brandon Brink.</i>

01:18.871 --> 01:20.120
<i> The last time I was here,</i>

01:20.164 --> 01:21.872
I ultimately got eliminated

01:21.916 --> 01:25.959
because my choice in
handle materials was below par.

01:26.003 --> 01:27.503
- You've got
a split handle here.

01:27.546 --> 01:31.507
- [bleep].
<i>Today, I hope to redeem myself.</i>

01:31.550 --> 01:34.802
Hopefully, everything will go
the way I plan it to.

01:34.845 --> 01:37.596
<i> - I'm JD Smith.</i>
<i> I'm 67 years old.</i>

01:37.640 --> 01:39.389
The first go-around,

01:39.433 --> 01:41.683
we were required to use
three different ingredients.

01:41.727 --> 01:44.353
<i> Unfortunately, I didn't pay</i>
<i> close enough attention</i>

01:44.396 --> 01:47.481
<i> to the instructions,</i>
<i> and I only used two.</i>

01:47.525 --> 01:49.441
<i> Hence, I had to get cut.</i>

01:49.485 --> 01:51.485
<i> It was a bit tough to swallow.</i>

01:51.529 --> 01:53.779
<i> The only thing I'm really</i>
<i> actually interested in proving</i>

01:53.823 --> 01:57.199
this go-around
is I'm as good

01:57.243 --> 01:59.618
as I think I am.

01:59.662 --> 02:01.954
- Welcome back to the Forge.

02:01.997 --> 02:04.581
Today, you get a second shot
at the title and redemption

02:04.625 --> 02:05.707
in front of the world

02:05.751 --> 02:07.501
and our panel of expert judges.

02:07.545 --> 02:09.169
Let's meet them now.

02:09.213 --> 02:11.755
Master bladesmith, Jason Knight,

02:11.799 --> 02:14.049
historic weapons
re-creation specialist,

02:14.093 --> 02:16.552
David Baker,
the deadliest man in this room,

02:16.595 --> 02:19.847
Kali martial artist,
Doug Marcaida.

02:19.890 --> 02:22.558
Today's competition,
you'll be using this.

02:22.601 --> 02:25.352
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:25.396 --> 02:28.105
two different types
of high-carbon steel,

02:28.149 --> 02:30.232
<i> which you are required</i>
<i> to fuse together with heat</i>

02:30.276 --> 02:32.860
<i> to form a Damascus billet.</i>

02:32.903 --> 02:34.444
<i> Sounds easy enough,</i>

02:34.488 --> 02:35.821
but your road to redemption

02:35.865 --> 02:38.240
is about to get
a little bit bumpier.

02:38.284 --> 02:39.908
From that billet of Damascus,

02:39.952 --> 02:41.368
you must forge
a signature blade

02:41.412 --> 02:43.495
in your signature style

02:43.539 --> 02:46.999
that also has a laddered
Damascus pattern.

02:47.042 --> 02:48.667
<i> Ladder patters are achieved</i>
<i> by cutting grooves</i>

02:48.711 --> 02:50.544
<i> into your Damascus billet.</i>

02:50.588 --> 02:52.921
<i> Once the grooves are pressed,</i>
<i> it is ground flat,</i>

02:52.965 --> 02:54.631
<i>removing all of the high spots,</i>

02:54.675 --> 02:56.925
<i> and then forged</i>
<i> to the desired blade shape,</i>

02:56.969 --> 02:59.136
<i> revealing a visible</i>
<i> ladder pattern.</i>

02:59.180 --> 03:01.013
<i> - Forge-welding</i>

03:01.056 --> 03:04.433
ladder-style Damascus--

03:04.476 --> 03:06.059
brother.

03:06.103 --> 03:08.437
- How you execute that pattern

03:08.480 --> 03:10.522
is also gonna be taken
into consideration

03:10.566 --> 03:12.024
during the judging.

03:12.067 --> 03:13.734
Keep in mind that
in the second round,

03:13.777 --> 03:15.319
you'll be attaching handles
to your blades

03:15.362 --> 03:17.487
to turn them into
fully-functional weapons

03:17.531 --> 03:19.364
that will then be
tested and judged

03:19.408 --> 03:20.407
based on how they perform

03:20.451 --> 03:22.451
in an ice block chop

03:22.494 --> 03:24.411
<i> and slicing through apples.</i>

03:24.455 --> 03:26.413
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

03:26.457 --> 03:29.499
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:29.543 --> 03:31.251
Good luck, bladesmiths.

03:31.295 --> 03:33.462
Your ten-minute design
window starts now.

03:33.505 --> 03:36.757
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

03:36.800 --> 03:39.301
Each one of these guys
has the opportunity

03:39.345 --> 03:40.928
to take the title.

03:40.971 --> 03:43.347
Each one of these guys
is capable of that.

03:43.390 --> 03:45.557
They just have to avoid
making the same costly mistakes

03:45.601 --> 03:48.227
they made last time
they were in the Forge.

03:48.270 --> 03:50.520
<i> - I have some experience</i>
<i> doing Damascus.</i>

03:50.564 --> 03:53.941
Mostly, it fails
and doesn't work. [laughs]

03:53.984 --> 03:56.151
<i> I'm making a chopper.</i>
<i> It's a type of knife</i>

03:56.195 --> 03:59.029
<i> that I've made before</i>
<i> and feel comfortable with.</i>

03:59.073 --> 04:01.365
<i> A chopper is good for</i>

04:01.408 --> 04:03.367
the type of tests
that we're gonna be doing.

04:03.410 --> 04:05.577
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:05.621 --> 04:06.703
<i> - I'm making a design</i>

04:06.747 --> 04:08.247
based on
a southeast Asian style,

04:08.290 --> 04:10.082
<i> called a barong.</i>

04:10.125 --> 04:11.667
<i> It's kind of</i>
<i> a leaf-shaped blade</i>

04:11.710 --> 04:14.169
<i> with a really drastic taper</i>
<i> and thickness,</i>

04:14.213 --> 04:16.922
<i> and there are multiple ways</i>
<i> to make a ladder pattern.</i>

04:16.966 --> 04:19.341
<i> The higher the layer count</i>
<i> in the billet, the more subtle</i>

04:19.385 --> 04:20.842
that grain is.

04:20.886 --> 04:23.303
<i> I'm gonna make</i>
<i> a 13-layer billet.</i>

04:23.347 --> 04:26.682
So this low layer pattern
is gonna be super-bold.

04:26.725 --> 04:29.101
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:29.144 --> 04:32.271
- This particular style of weld
that they're asking us to do,

04:32.314 --> 04:33.522
I've never done before.

04:33.565 --> 04:35.274
<i> But I know that I want to do</i>

04:35.317 --> 04:37.442
<i>some kind of Bowie-style knife.</i>

04:37.486 --> 04:41.947
<i> Beefy, scary, hardcore,</i>
<i> gonna get the job done.</i>

04:41.991 --> 04:43.824
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:43.867 --> 04:45.325
<i> - I've decided</i>
<i> I'm making something</i>

04:45.369 --> 04:48.412
that's very close
to a Pilipino parang,

04:48.455 --> 04:51.081
<i> kind of a leaf-shaped blade</i>
<i> that's gonna be good</i>

04:51.125 --> 04:53.583
<i> for chopping</i>
<i> and also for slicing.</i>

04:53.627 --> 04:56.461
<i> Pattern-welded steel</i>
<i> is a passion of mine.</i>

04:56.505 --> 04:58.297
<i> So I'm gonna be going</i>
<i> for a number of layers</i>

04:58.340 --> 04:59.756
<i> that's perhaps going to be</i>

04:59.800 --> 05:02.050
a bit higher
than the other contestants,

05:02.094 --> 05:04.845
and I'm hoping that's going to
make my blade

05:04.888 --> 05:07.180
<i> stand out above theirs.</i>

05:07.224 --> 05:09.391
- Your ten-minute design
window is closed.

05:09.435 --> 05:13.061
Your three-hour forge
time starts now.

05:13.105 --> 05:16.898
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:16.942 --> 05:19.359
- First challenge
to overcome: Damascus.

05:19.403 --> 05:21.737
Second challenge: ladder it.

05:21.780 --> 05:24.906
- I have never,
ever even attempted

05:24.950 --> 05:26.783
<i> to do a ladder-style Damascus.</i>

05:26.827 --> 05:29.828
So this is gonna be
a first for me.

05:29.872 --> 05:32.914
- It looks like Brandon
is wrapping all of his pieces

05:32.958 --> 05:35.834
of steel together
with baling wire.

05:35.878 --> 05:39.338
- He can do that.
That is an old-school technique.

05:39.381 --> 05:41.631
- It's really interesting that
that's what he chose to do,

05:41.675 --> 05:44.843
and it seems like welding
with the MIG welder

05:44.887 --> 05:46.845
would be a lot more secure.

05:46.889 --> 05:49.598
- Well, Brandon was here
on our last challenge

05:49.641 --> 05:51.600
with a cold forge,
no electricity or anything.

05:51.643 --> 05:54.353
It might be his comfort zone.

05:54.396 --> 05:57.814
But in a competition like this,
use what's available to you.

05:57.858 --> 06:00.650
-<i> I consider myself a purist.</i>

06:00.694 --> 06:02.152
<i> I like to do</i>
<i> everything by hand.</i>

06:02.196 --> 06:04.696
You know, files and hammers--

06:04.740 --> 06:07.157
<i> I'm trying to get away</i>
<i> from modern technology</i>

06:07.201 --> 06:09.284
and go back to the way
it was 100, 200,

06:09.328 --> 06:10.827
<i> even 1,000 years ago.</i>

06:10.871 --> 06:13.580
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:13.624 --> 06:15.415
- Oh!
- [bleep].

06:15.459 --> 06:17.376
- I think his wire's broken,

06:17.419 --> 06:19.169
and he might be in trouble.

06:19.213 --> 06:22.214
- Yeah, I'm having an issue.

06:22.257 --> 06:24.174
[bleep].

06:24.218 --> 06:27.177
- Well, this is gonna be either
a success or a disaster.

06:27.221 --> 06:31.098
- Let's try this again.

06:31.141 --> 06:33.266
- We got JD and Clarence
over here,

06:33.310 --> 06:35.102
working side-by-side.

06:35.145 --> 06:36.978
<i> - You have to get a good weld</i>
<i> when you begin.</i>

06:37.022 --> 06:38.605
Obviously, that's key.

06:38.649 --> 06:40.732
<i> It's got to be</i>
<i> a solid piece of steel.</i>

06:40.776 --> 06:43.735
<i> I've got everything welded up</i>
<i> as good as it needs to be.</i>

06:43.779 --> 06:46.071
<i> Time to put it in the forge</i>
<i> and have a go at it.</i>

06:46.115 --> 06:48.281
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:48.325 --> 06:50.909
- Where making laddered
Damascus is concerned,

06:50.953 --> 06:53.578
I've actually done this before.

06:53.622 --> 06:57.040
I'm certainly as good as some
and better than most.

06:57.084 --> 06:58.834
- Here's an interesting fact.

06:58.877 --> 07:01.878
The first time that Gabe
ever forged Damascus,

07:01.922 --> 07:05.507
he was at JD's forge.
- [laughs]

07:05.551 --> 07:07.092
- How funny is that?

07:07.136 --> 07:08.802
You've got the teacher

07:08.846 --> 07:12.722
and the student
both jockeying for redemption,

07:12.766 --> 07:14.808
and somebody's gotta lose.

07:14.852 --> 07:16.810
<i> - I met JD when I was</i>
<i> eight years old.</i>

07:16.854 --> 07:18.562
I've always admired his work.

07:18.605 --> 07:21.273
So to be, you know,
challenged against the best,

07:21.316 --> 07:22.607
that's--I want to test myself,

07:22.651 --> 07:26.111
and that is definitely a test.

07:26.155 --> 07:28.738
<i> - Gabe claims</i>
<i> I'm the person who taught him</i>

07:28.782 --> 07:31.116
laddered Damascus,
but I don't actually

07:31.160 --> 07:33.660
remember the occasion.
[laughs]

07:33.704 --> 07:36.621
<i> But at my age, there's a lot</i>
<i> of things I don't remember.</i>

07:36.665 --> 07:38.582
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:38.625 --> 07:40.625
- Wow.
- Man, look at how pretty that

07:40.669 --> 07:42.169
all just folded up.

07:42.212 --> 07:44.421
That was gorgeous, man.
- Origami.

07:44.465 --> 07:46.381
- That was amazing.

07:46.425 --> 07:49.301
JD over here,
demonstrating exactly

07:49.344 --> 07:54.222
what it means
to be a master at Damascus.

07:54.266 --> 07:56.725
You have just two hours
remaining to finish your work!

07:56.768 --> 07:58.685
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:58.729 --> 08:00.395
<i> - As I'm working, I realize</i>

08:00.439 --> 08:03.607
I want more layers in my billet.

08:03.650 --> 08:06.401
<i> I watched JD do this</i>
<i> folding process,</i>

08:06.445 --> 08:09.029
<i> so I'm gonna do it</i>
<i> the same way.</i>

08:09.072 --> 08:11.323
- He's got his billet
in the vice.

08:11.366 --> 08:13.658
- Good. He's going for
60 layers as well.

08:13.702 --> 08:16.411
- Not quite as smooth as JD,
but he's making it happen.

08:16.455 --> 08:18.121
- Hit. it. Hit it.
Hit it. Hit it.

08:18.165 --> 08:21.374
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:21.418 --> 08:24.669
- [bleep] damn it.
Son of a bitch.

08:24.713 --> 08:26.213
- Brandon's struggling

08:26.256 --> 08:28.173
with individual pieces of steel,

08:28.217 --> 08:30.091
trying to tack them together

08:30.135 --> 08:32.969
by forge-welding
each individual piece.

08:33.013 --> 08:36.640
It's time-consuming
and hard to watch.

08:36.683 --> 08:39.226
- [bleep] damn, dude.
My welds aren't sticking.

08:39.269 --> 08:41.144
My pieces are
all over the place,

08:41.188 --> 08:43.647
<i> and it's similar to nails</i>
<i> on the chalkboard</i>

08:43.690 --> 08:46.233
and nails in your ears.

08:46.276 --> 08:48.151
It's just-- [growls]
Damn it, man.

08:48.195 --> 08:50.612
<i> Come on.</i>

08:50.656 --> 08:51.947
Hey, it held together.

08:51.990 --> 08:55.534
Look at that [bleep].

08:55.577 --> 08:57.786
[bleep], yeah.

08:57.829 --> 08:59.162
Get you hot, and we're gonna
throw your ass

08:59.206 --> 09:01.206
under the hammer, [bleep].

09:01.250 --> 09:04.292
- I do not know
how he can possibly stretch

09:04.336 --> 09:06.044
that blade out enough to--

09:06.088 --> 09:07.462
- But we said that before,

09:07.506 --> 09:09.464
and he made it happen.

09:09.508 --> 09:11.508
<i> Just like he did last time,</i>
<i> he chased the problem</i>

09:11.552 --> 09:13.677
<i> for half of that time,</i>

09:13.720 --> 09:15.262
<i> and then he got locked on,</i>

09:15.305 --> 09:17.472
and he ended up
moving onto the next round.

09:17.516 --> 09:21.935
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:21.979 --> 09:25.313
Gabe's got his billet locked up
in a vise, and he's drawing in

09:25.357 --> 09:28.066
his ladder pattern
with an angle grinder.

09:28.110 --> 09:29.609
<i> - JD Smith taught me</i>

09:29.653 --> 09:32.279
two main points
about making a ladder pattern.

09:32.322 --> 09:33.655
<i> One is that the depth</i>
<i> of the ladder</i>

09:33.699 --> 09:35.907
<i> should be about a third</i>
<i> of the billet,</i>

09:35.951 --> 09:37.409
<i> and then,</i>
<i> these ladder patterns</i>

09:37.452 --> 09:39.077
should also be alternating.

09:39.121 --> 09:41.997
So they're offset,
one side from the other.

09:42.040 --> 09:43.915
If you don't grind the rungs
deep enough,

09:43.959 --> 09:45.417
the pattern won't be visible

09:45.460 --> 09:47.877
<i> when you forge</i>
<i> your blade out to shape.</i>

09:47.921 --> 09:51.381
I do my ladder pattern
exactly how JD taught me.

09:51.425 --> 09:53.508
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

09:53.552 --> 09:56.720
- You have one hour remaining
to finish your work!

09:56.763 --> 09:59.306
- [groans]

09:59.349 --> 10:00.849
<i> - Standing in front of</i>
<i> the forge</i>

10:00.892 --> 10:02.684
is quite hot.

10:02.728 --> 10:05.645
<i> It's in excess</i>
<i> of 1,800 degrees Fahrenheit,</i>

10:05.689 --> 10:09.316
plus the fact I've got
another one directly at my back.

10:09.359 --> 10:10.442
<i> So I'm basically cooking</i>

10:10.485 --> 10:13.903
between two forges.

10:13.947 --> 10:16.531
- Worried a little bit
about JD here.

10:16.575 --> 10:18.491
<i> - Starting to feel actually</i>

10:18.535 --> 10:21.411
a little queasy and unwell.

10:21.455 --> 10:24.414
<i> I'm fighting to just</i>
<i> maintain consciousness.</i>

10:24.458 --> 10:27.542
<i> I'm fearing I just won't be</i>
<i> able to continue at all.</i>

10:27.586 --> 10:30.337
- Hey, let's get the medic
over there.

10:30.380 --> 10:32.839
- JD's about to go down.

10:42.851 --> 10:44.893
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

10:44.936 --> 10:47.771
- Okay. You need to sit down.
- Oh.

10:47.814 --> 10:49.606
Oh.

10:49.650 --> 10:52.275
- So our medic's over there,
checking out JD.

10:52.319 --> 10:53.652
- Ahh.
- All right. I'm gonna

10:53.695 --> 10:55.820
put this one under your shirt.
- Ohh.

10:55.864 --> 10:58.114
- Hopefully, he doesn't
lose much time,

10:58.158 --> 11:00.617
and he comes back,
and he can make it happen.

11:00.661 --> 11:02.744
This is not an easy competition.

11:02.788 --> 11:04.496
It can take its toll.

11:04.539 --> 11:08.541
This Forge breaks people down,

11:08.585 --> 11:10.710
physically and mentally.

11:10.754 --> 11:12.712
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:12.756 --> 11:15.423
Clarence is starting to work
on his ladder pattern.

11:15.467 --> 11:17.884
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

11:17.928 --> 11:19.511
Gabe is cruising right along.

11:19.554 --> 11:22.681
He's over there
on the 72-inch belt grinder.

11:22.724 --> 11:25.850
- So here's what I'm really
amazed by--

11:25.894 --> 11:28.019
how much knife Brandon got

11:28.063 --> 11:30.188
out of that piece of steel.

11:30.232 --> 11:31.898
- He'll be able to do surgery
with that thing,

11:31.942 --> 11:33.400
but I don't know
about chopping ice.

11:36.905 --> 11:38.154
